body:
It fixes validation of React methods order.

For example, when I had:

``` js
const Input = React.createClass({
  componentDidMount() {
    console.log('mounted');
  },

  getInitialState() {
    return {
      a: 1,
    };
  },
});
```

Linter showed no errors. That happened because of `/^get.+$/` regexp. It matched with getInitalState so it was allowed to place `getInitialState` below `componentDidMount`.

In JavaScript ES5 Type Casting [Section](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript/tree/master/es5#type-casting--coercion)
-  **Perform type coercion at the beginning of the statement.**

``` javascript
// bad
var totalScore = '' + this.reviewScore + ' total score';

// good
var totalScore = this.reviewScore + ' total score';
```

Based on the guide, should the first statement is good and the last is bad?
